<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-998-432  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 998 432.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Dec 1989 v6 n12 p95(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Selling insurance: users want to buy insurance against the latestsecurity risks, but the buying is hard.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crater, Alan K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses present a unique challenge to insuranceunderwriters.andP;  In existence since the mid-1980s, computer viruseshave evolved in complex ways and hold the potential forcatastrophic destruction of data and loss of informational andfinancial resources.andP;  A complex deliberation is underway todetermine the insurance implications of such a threat and itsrelation to corporate EDP policy.andP;  The direction of the thinkingof underwriters is to consider the result of the virus from thepoint of view of the insured.andP;  There are three probable categoriesof loss involved: loss of data, loss of media capacity andderangement of data.andP;  The key clause from the EDP underwriter'sperspective is to determine what types of loss are excluded from apolicy.andP;  Key concerns include modes of access, extent of internalsecurity measures, backup programs in place, duplicationprovisions, testing and contingency plans.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Insurance IndustryComputer CrimesComputer VirusesData SecurityCost EstimationEDP Budgeting.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Computer system vulnerability to a computer virus. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>